04718nam a22006255i 9780674020368DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212010mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740203687 a10.4159/97806740203682doi  a(DE-B1597)584850  a(OCoLC)1257323728  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a955.051 aAzimi, Fakhreddin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Quest for Democracy in Iran :bA Century of Struggle against Authoritarian Rule /cFakhreddin Azimi. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (512 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote on Transliteration -- tPrologue: In Search of a National Covenant -- tPart I. Constituting a National Community (1906–1953) -- t1. Constitutional Trial and Error -- t2. Pahlavist Absolutism -- t3. Restoration of Parliamentary Politics -- tPart II. Authoritarian Supremacy: Consolidation and Collapse (1953–1979) -- t4. The Trajectories of Monarchism -- t5. Revolution: Chronicle of an Implosion -- t6. The Edifice and Emplacements of Royal Rule -- t7. Elective Affinities: Western Imperial Interests and Authoritarian Monarchy -- t8. The Architecture of Royalist Hegemony -- t9. A Culture of Confrontation -- tPart III. The Eclipse of Popular Sovereignty: Iran since 1979 -- t10. The Unfolding of Clerical Rule: Oligarchy by Divine Right? -- t11. The Culture of Politics: The Presence and Absence of the Past -- t12. Predicaments and Prospects -- tEpilogue: The Resilience of Modernity -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"The Constitutional Revolution of 1906 launched Iran as a pioneer in a broad-based movement to establish democratic rule in the non-Western world. In a book that provides essential context for understanding modern Iran, Fakhreddin Azimi traces a century of struggle for the establishment of representative government. The promise of constitutional rule was cut short in the 1920s with the rise of the Pahlavi dynasty. Reza Shah, whose despotic rule Azimi deftly captures, maintained the façade of a constitutional monarch but greeted any challenge with an iron fist: “I will eliminate you,” he routinely barked at his officials. In 1941, fearful of losing control of the oil-rich region, the Allies forced Reza Shah to abdicate but allowed Mohammad Reza to succeed his father. Though promising to abide by the constitution, the new Shah missed no opportunity to undermine it. The Anglo-American–backed coup of 1953, which ousted reformist premier Mohammed Mosaddeq, dealt a blow to the constitutionalists. The Shah’s repressive policies and subservience to the United States radicalized both secular and religious opponents, leading to the revolution of 1979. Azimi argues that we have fundamentally misunderstood this event by characterizing it as an “Islamic” revolution when it was in reality the expression of a long-repressed desire for popular sovereignty. This explains why the clerical rulers have failed to counter the growing public conviction that the Islamic Republic, too, is impervious to political reform—and why the democratic impulse that began with the Constitutional Revolution continues to be a potent and resilient force."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracyxIran. 0aDemocracyzIran. 0aDémocratiexIran. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674020368423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674020368.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  